If you don't get into the discussion, you won't get into the class. I recommend switching to a discussion that has more seats open than there are people on the waitlist. That way you can definitely get into a discussion, hence the class.

If the class goes to 100% full enrollment, then that means that the class is full. There's no reason to expect that the class would be expanded.

If expanding did occur, it would more likely be due to adding new sections.

children.subject: You can see your waitlist position in lecture through cal central under my academics. To my knowledge there's no way of knowing your discussion position. You cause use schedule of classes to check discussion section open seats.

If you are enrolled in the course, you can use the Options menu to change sections.

If you are waitlisted, then there is no way of changing what section you are waitlisted for, other than dropping / reenrolling.

How to see the my waitlisted position on dis or lecture?

What is the steps to switch to another discussion on CalCentral?

How to check open seats on discussion sections?

Can anyone help me?

Depends on your particular situation / risk preference, I suppose.

You can't switch sections without dropping if you're waitlisted.

Whether switching out is better or not partially depends on how much more open the section you're switching to is.

Hypothetical:

  • CS188
  • Student is #40 on waitlist, waitlist total is 500 students long
  • It's day 1 of adjustment period
  • Student enrolls into a discussion with 100 seats, 10 enrolled, and 10 waitslisted (so there are way more open seats than there are waitlisted for the discussion section)

What happens? Does the student move off the waitlist entirely because he/she got into a discussion section? 

Basically I want to know how the waitlist is processed. Are there actually individual waitlists for each discussion section, and that's the one you want to move off of? If that's the case then the waitlist rank for the course as a whole is pretty useless since it doesn't tell you anything about your chance of getting into the class. You could be #500 on the waitlist for the course, but #1 for your discussion section and suddenly leapfrog all 499 people ahead of you on the course waitlist. 

Or is that not how it works? If not, then how?

There are not individual waitlists for each individual section. There is only a single waitlist for the entire course.

If there are enough open seats in the lecture, then this student would get into the course, yes, because they would be the first person on the course waitlist who can get into both lecture + discussion.

Yes, the waitlist position number is not the most important factor as to whether you'll get into the course; section is usually harder to get into than lecture, so that typically matters more.

So I guess a question is, if you don't know your discussion waitlist position, would you still recommend switching to another discussion section? At this point I believe most discussions are full for most CS classes anyways?

And switching to different discussion sections -- can you switch sections without dropping the class for waitlisted classes? And if not, then wouldn't switching out (at this time) just be even worse?
